  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. Back in my days as a high school student, I remember how the idea that 'math isn't for everyone' made me nervous when I'd get stuck on a problem. Now, as an electrician in New York, I see it in the way some young people avoid physics or engineering because they think they're not 'good at it.' Stereotype threat is when someone's fear of confirming a negative stereotype about their group affects their performance. For instance, if a girl thinks she's not good at math, she might not try as hard, or she might give up quickly. I've noticed this in my own community—my daughter, who's a bright girl, sometimes hesitates to take advanced math courses because she's worried about being labeled as 'not smart enough.' We need to address this issue head-on. First, teachers and mentors should create environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. Second, we need to challenge stereotypes early on, not just in classrooms but in everyday conversations. For example, when I talk to my neighbors about their kids' school projects, I make sure to emphasize that effort and curiosity matter more than innate talent. It's not about fixing people—it's about changing the narrative so that everyone knows they belong in STEM. As someone who's lived through this and seen it affect others, I believe addressing stereotype threat is crucial. It's not just a matter of policy—it's about building confidence in the next generation.",
